   <abstract>Opothle Yoholo served as the principal councilor (sometimes called the speaker of the council) in the Creek towns on the Tallapoosa and Coosa rivers in Alabama. He took part in the 1826 Creek delegation to Washington, DC to argue against the Treaty of Indian Springs. Although he remained steadfast in his opposition to the US Government's plans to relocate the Creek, he led a group of Creek warriors against the Seminole during the Creek War of 1836 and later removed to Arkansas voluntarily. This print was taken from a portrait painted by Charles Bird King in 1826. The original has since been destroyed by fire.</abstract>
